{
  "analysis": "I'm starting with a fresh terminal session in the /app directory. My first step is to examine the input JSON file to understand its structure and contents before proceeding with the transformation.",
  "plan": "I'll use the 'ls' command to check what files are in the /app directory, then use 'cat' to view the contents of the users.json file to understand its structure.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I can see the users.json file exists in the /app directory. Now I need to examine its contents to understand the data structure before creating the jq transformation.",
  "plan": "I'll use the 'head' command to view the beginning of the users.json file to get a sense of its structure.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "head -n 20 users.json\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I can see the structure of the users.json file. It's an array of user objects with the expected fields: id, username, email, status, last_login, and roles. I've seen enough to start crafting the jq command. Now I need to create the jq transformation that will filter active users, format the dates, extract and rename fields, and sort the results.",
  "plan": "I'll craft a jq command that does all the required transformations:\n1. Filter users with status 'active'\n2. Transform each user object to have the required fields\n3. Sort by username\n4. Format with 2-space indentation\n\nLet me build and test this command step by step.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq '[.[] | select(.status == \"active\") | {user_id: .id, username: .username, email: .email, last_login: (.last_login | strptime(\"%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%fZ\") | strftime(\"%Y-%m-%d\")), role_count: (.roles | length), primary_role: (if (.roles | length) > 0 then .roles[0] else null end)}] | sort_by(.username)' users.json | head -n 15\n",
      "duration": 2.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I encountered an error with the date parsing. The issue seems to be with the fractional seconds format specifier. Let me try a different approach to parse the ISO 8601 timestamp.",
  "plan": "I'll modify the jq command to use a simpler approach for parsing the ISO 8601 timestamp. Instead of using strptime with %f, I'll split the string and take only the date part.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq '[.[] | select(.status == \"active\") | {user_id: .id, username: .username, email: .email, last_login: (.last_login | split(\"T\")[0]), role_count: (.roles | length), primary_role: (if (.roles | length) > 0 then .roles[0] else null end)}] | sort_by(.username)' users.json | head -n 15\n",
      "duration": 2.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The jq command is working correctly now. I can see the transformed data with the correct structure. The output shows user_id, username, email, last_login in YYYY-MM-DD format, role_count, and primary_role. The data is also sorted by username. Now I need to save this command to cmd.sh and create the jq_args.yaml file as required.",
  "plan": "I'll create the final jq command that outputs to the required file, save the command to cmd.sh, and create the jq_args.yaml file with the filter and arguments.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'jq \\'[.[] | select(.status == \"active\") | {user_id: .id, username: .username, email: .email, last_login: (.last_login | split(\"T\")[0]), role_count: (.roles | length), primary_role: (if (.roles | length) > 0 then .roles[0] else null end)}] | sort_by(.username)\\' users.json > active_users_report.json' > cmd.sh\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I encountered a syntax error when trying to create the cmd.sh file. This is because of the parentheses in the jq command which are being interpreted by the shell. I need to properly escape the command when saving it to the file.",
  "plan": "I'll fix the cmd.sh creation by properly escaping the parentheses and other special characters. Then I'll run the command to generate the output file and create the jq_args.yaml file.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'jq \"[.[] | select(.status == \\\"active\\\") | {user_id: .id, username: .username, email: .email, last_login: (.last_login | split(\\\"T\\\")[0]), role_count: (.roles | length), primary_role: (if (.roles | length) > 0 then .roles[0] else null end)}] | sort_by(.username)\" users.json > active_users_report.json' > cmd.sh\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I've successfully created the cmd.sh file with the proper escaping. Now I need to execute this command to generate the output file and create the jq_args.yaml file with the required information.",
  "plan": "First, I'll execute the command in cmd.sh to generate the active_users_report.json file. Then I'll create the jq_args.yaml file with the filter expression and arguments.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "chmod +x cmd.sh\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I've made the cmd.sh file executable. Now I'll run it to generate the active_users_report.json file.",
  "plan": "Execute the cmd.sh script to generate the report file, then create the jq_args.yaml file with the required information.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "./cmd.sh\n",
      "duration": 2.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The cmd.sh script executed without errors. Now I need to verify that the active_users_report.json file was created correctly and then create the jq_args.yaml file.",
  "plan": "First, I'll check if the active_users_report.json file exists and examine its contents to ensure it's properly formatted. Then I'll create the jq_args.yaml file with the required filter and arguments.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la active_users_report.json\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The active_users_report.json file has been created successfully. Now I need to verify its contents and create the jq_args.yaml file.",
  "plan": "I'll check the beginning of the active_users_report.json file to verify it has the correct structure. Then I'll create the jq_args.yaml file with the filter expression and arguments.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "head -n 15 active_users_report.json\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The active_users_report.json file looks good. It has the correct structure with user_id, username, email, last_login in YYYY-MM-DD format, role_count, and primary_role. The data is also sorted by username. Now I need to create the jq_args.yaml file with the filter expression and arguments.",
  "plan": "I'll create the jq_args.yaml file with the required filter expression and arguments. Based on my command, I need to extract the filter and any additional arguments for jq.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat > jq_args.yaml << 'EOF'\nfilter: \"[.[] | select(.status == \\\"active\\\") | {user_id: .id, username: .username, email: .email, last_login: (.last_login | split(\\\"T\\\")[0]), role_count: (.roles | length), primary_role: (if (.roles | length) > 0 then .roles[0] else null end)}] | sort_by(.username)\"\nargs: []\nEOF\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "I've created the jq_args.yaml file with the filter expression. Since my jq command doesn't use any additional arguments beyond the filter, the args list is empty. Let me verify the content of the YAML file to ensure it's correctly formatted.",
  "plan": "I'll check the content of the jq_args.yaml file to make sure it's properly formatted. Then I'll validate that the generated files meet all the requirements.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat jq_args.yaml\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The jq_args.yaml file looks good. It contains the filter expression and an empty args list since my jq command doesn't require additional arguments. Let me also verify the cmd.sh file content to ensure it matches our requirements.",
  "plan": "I'll check the content of cmd.sh to make sure it contains the correct jq command. Then I'll validate that all requirements have been met.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat cmd.sh\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Both the cmd.sh and jq_args.yaml files look correct. Let me now verify that the active_users_report.json file meets all the requirements by checking more of its content and ensuring proper formatting.",
  "plan": "I'll examine more of the active_users_report.json file to verify it's properly formatted with 2-space indentation and contains all the required fields. I'll also check that it only includes active users and that they're sorted by username.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "tail -n +15 active_users_report.json | head -n 20\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The output shows that the data is properly formatted with 2-space indentation and contains all the required fields. I can see that usernames are sorted alphabetically (allencarlos, allentracy, alyssasanders). Let me verify that we only have active users in the output.",
  "plan": "I'll check if there are any inactive users in the original file and confirm that they're not present in our output. Then I'll verify the total count of users to ensure completeness.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq '.[] | select(.status == \"inactive\") | .username' users.json | wc -l\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "There are 123 inactive users in the original file. Let me check how many active users we have in our output to make sure our filtering worked correctly.",
  "plan": "I'll count the number of users in the active_users_report.json file to verify that it matches the number of active users in the original file.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq 'length' active_users_report.json\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Let me check the total number of users in the original file to confirm our numbers add up correctly.",
  "plan": "I'll count the total number of users in the original file and verify that it equals the sum of active and inactive users.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq 'length' users.json\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The numbers add up correctly: 322 active users + 123 inactive users = 445 users. Wait, that doesn't equal 500. Let me double-check my math and verify the counts again.",
  "plan": "I'll recount the active users in the original file to make sure I have the right numbers.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq '.[] | select(.status == \"active\") | .username' users.json | wc -l\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Now I have confirmed that there are 322 active users and 123 inactive users, totaling 445 users. But the original file has 500 users. There seems to be a discrepancy of 55 users. Let me check if there are any users with statuses other than 'active' or 'inactive'.",
  "plan": "I'll check for any users that don't have 'active' or 'inactive' as their status to account for the missing 55 users.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq '.[] | select(.status != \"active\" and .status != \"inactive\") | .status' users.json | wc -l\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "That explains the discrepancy. There are 55 users with statuses other than 'active' or 'inactive'. Our task specifically asks for only 'active' users, so our output of 322 users is correct. Let me verify one more aspect of our output - that the dates are properly formatted.",
  "plan": "I'll check a few entries in the output file to verify that the last_login field is properly formatted as YYYY-MM-DD.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq '.[0:3] | .[].last_login' active_users_report.json\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The dates are properly formatted as YYYY-MM-DD. Let me also verify that the primary_role field is correctly set to null when there are no roles.",
  "plan": "I'll check if there are any users with empty roles arrays and verify that their primary_role is set to null.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq '.[] | select(.role_count == 0) | .primary_role' active_users_report.json | head -n 5\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Everything looks good. The primary_role is correctly set to null for users with no roles. I've verified that:\n1. Only active users are included\n2. The output is sorted by username\n3. Dates are formatted as YYYY-MM-DD\n4. All required fields are present\n5. Primary_role is null when there are no roles\n6. The cmd.sh file contains the correct jq command\n7. The jq_args.yaml file contains the filter expression\n\nAll requirements have been met.",
  "plan": "Final verification - I'll run the command specified in the task description to ensure that the jq_args.yaml file works correctly when used with yq to construct the jq command.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "jq $(yq -r '.args[]' jq_args.yaml) \"$(yq -r '.filter' jq_args.yaml)\" users.json | head -n 5\n",
      "duration": 2.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": true
}
